---
import PageLayout from '../../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from '../../config';
---

<PageLayout
  title="How to Fix Invalid JSON — Common Errors and Quick Checks"
  description="Learn how to fix invalid JSON by checking quotes, commas, escaping, brackets, comments and copied API payloads. Includes a practical browser-only workflow."
  h1="How to Fix Invalid JSON"
  path="/guides/how-to-fix-invalid-json"
  article
  published="2026-07-09"
  updated="2026-07-20"
>
  <p>
    Invalid JSON usually comes from a small syntax problem: one extra comma, one missing quote or a
    copied value that still contains unescaped line breaks. The fastest way to fix it is to validate
    the text, find the exact line where parsing stops and then clean only the broken part instead of
    rewriting the whole file.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you already have the payload, paste it into the <a href="/json">JSON Formatter &amp; Validator</a>
    first. It runs in your browser, so API responses, config snippets and prompt logs are not uploaded
    to a server.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with the parser error</h2>
  <p>
    JSON parsers usually report the first place where they can no longer understand the document. That
    point is often slightly after the real mistake, so check the line above the reported error as well.
    Look for a missing comma between properties, an unfinished string or a bracket that closes too soon.
  </p>

  <h2>Check quotes and property names</h2>
  <p>
    JSON requires double quotes around object keys and string values. Single quotes, smart quotes from a
    document editor and unquoted property names are valid in some JavaScript examples but not in JSON.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Use <code>"name"</code>, not <code>'name'</code> or <code>name</code>.</li>
    <li>Use plain double quotes, not curly “smart” quotes.</li>
    <li>Escape quotes inside strings as <code>\"</code>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Remove trailing commas</h2>
  <p>
    A trailing comma after the last item in an object or array will break strict JSON. This often
    happens when copying from JavaScript, TypeScript or documentation examples.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Invalid: <code>&#123;"role":"user",&#125;</code></li>
    <li>Valid: <code>&#123;"role":"user"&#125;</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Escape line breaks inside strings</h2>
  <p>
    Raw line breaks are not allowed inside JSON strings. If a value contains a prompt, Markdown block or
    email body, line breaks must be escaped as <code>\n</code>. When you are reading LLM request logs,
    the <a href="/prompt">AI Prompt Formatter</a> can make escaped prompt text easier to inspect before
    you copy a nested JSON block into the JSON validator.
  </p>

  <h2>Do not include comments</h2>
  <p>
    Standard JSON does not support <code>//</code> or <code>/* ... */</code> comments. If your source is
    a config-like file with comments, remove those comments before sending it to an API that expects
    JSON.
  </p>

  <h2>Match every bracket and brace</h2>
  <p>
    Objects use braces, arrays use brackets and every opening character needs the matching close:
    <code>&#123;&#125;</code> for objects and <code>[]</code> for arrays. A formatter helps here because valid
    nested JSON becomes visibly indented, while broken nesting usually fails before it can be formatted.
  </p>

  <h2>A quick fixing workflow</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Paste the payload into the <a href="/json">JSON Formatter &amp; Validator</a>.</li>
    <li>Read the reported line and column, then check that line and the line above it.</li>
    <li>Fix quotes, commas, comments, unescaped newlines or mismatched brackets.</li>
    <li>Validate again and repeat until the JSON formats cleanly.</li>
    <li>Use minify only after the formatted version is valid and readable.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When invalid JSON comes from AI logs</h2>
  <p>
    LLM logs often contain JSON inside JSON: a request body may include a messages array, and each
    message may include escaped prompt text. For that case, start with the
    <a href="/prompt">AI Prompt Formatter</a> to separate roles and unescape the prompt, then use
    <a href="/pretty-print-prompt-json">Pretty Print Prompt JSON</a> or the
    <a href="/json">JSON Formatter</a> for the nested payload.
  </p>

  <h2>Related tools on {SITE.name}</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/prompt">AI Prompt Formatter</a> for readable prompt logs.</li>
    <li><a href="/json">JSON Formatter &amp; Validator</a> for syntax checks and pretty printing.</li>
    <li><a href="/unescape-prompt">Unescape Prompt</a> for copied strings with literal escape sequences.</li>
  </ul>
</PageLayout>
